{
  "doc_id": "50417",
  "text": "The EC system at the Bugac site has been measuring the CO 2 and sensible and latent heat fluxes continuously since 2002. In dry years the grassland can turn into a net carbon source [CITATION_1] , but the longer-term annual sums of net ecosystem exchange (NEE) show it to be a net sink, ranging from -171 to +106 g C m -2 yr -1 [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] with a -100 g C m -2 yr -1 average. The EC system consists of a CSAT3 sonic anemometer (Campbell Scientific, USA) and a Li-7500 (Licor Inc, USA) open-path infra-red gas analyzer (at the height of 4 m, anemometer direction: north), both connected to a CR5000 data logger (Campbell Scientific, USA) via an SDM (synchronous device for measurement) interface. Additional measurements used in the present study included air temperature and relative humidity (HMP35AC, Vaisala, Finland), precipitation (ARG 100 rain gauge, Campbell, UK), global radiation (dual pyranometer, Schenk, Austria from 2002 and CMP3, Kipp&Zonen, The Netherlands from 2013) incoming and reflected photosynthetically active radiation (SKP215, Campbell, UK), volumetric soil moisture content (CS616, Campbell, UK) and soil temperature (105T, Campbell, UK). Surface temperature (T surf ) was measured by 3 cm above the ground under the leaves. These measurements were performed as described by Nagy et al. and Pintér et al. [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Fluxes of sensible and latent heat and CO 2 were processed by EddyPro 1 [CITATION_6] using double rotation, linear detrending and WPL correction [CITATION_7] . Gap-filling and flux partitioning was performed by the REddyProc online data processing tool [CITATION_8] . Diel pattern of soil respiration among phenological stages",
